Stephen Dedalus is the main character ofA Portrait of the Artist as a Young Man.Growing up, Stephen goes through long phases of hedonism and deep religiosity. He eventually adopts a philosophy of aestheticism, greatly valuing beauty and art. Stephen is essentially Joyce's alter ego, and many of the events of Stephen's life mirror events from Joyce's own youth.
Simon Dedalus is Stephen's father, an impoverished former medical student with a strong sense of Irish patriotism. Sentimental about his past, Simon Dedalus frequently reminisces about his youth.
Mary Dedalus is Stephen's mother and Simon Dedalus's wife. Mary is very religious, and argues with her son about attending religious services.
The Dedalus Children is Though his siblings do not play a major role in the novel, Stephen has several brothers and sisters, including Maurice, Katey, Maggie, and Boody.
Emma Clery is Stephen's beloved, the young girl to whom he is fiercely attracted over the course of many years. Stephen constructs Emma as an ideal of femininity, even though he does not know her well.
Mr. John Casey is Simon Dedalus's friend, who attends the Christmas dinner at which young Stephen is allowed to sit with the adults for the first time. Like Simon, Mr. Casey is a staunch believer in Irish nationalism, and at the dinner he argues with Dante over the fate of Parnell.
Charles Stewart Parnell is an Irish political leader who is not an actual character in the novel, but whose death influences many of its characters. Parnell had powerfully led the Irish National Party until he was condemned for having an affair with a married woman.
Dante (Mrs. Riordan) is the extremely fervent and piously Catholic governess of the Dedalus children. Dante, whose real name is Mrs. Riordan, becomes involved in a long and unpleasant argument with Mr. Casey over the fate of Parnell during Christmas dinner.
Uncle Charles is Stephen's lively great uncle. Charles lives with Stephen's family. During the summer, the young Stephen enjoys taking long walks with his uncle and listening to Charles and Simon discuss the history of both Ireland and the Dedalus family.
Eileen Vance is a young girl who lives near Stephen when he is a young boy. When Stephen tells Dante that he wants to marry Eileen, Dante is enraged because Eileen is a Protestant.
Father Conmee is the rector at Clongowes Wood College, where Stephen attends school as a young boy.
Father Dolan is the cruel prefect of studies at Clongowes Wood College.
Wells is the bully at Clongowes. Wells taunts Stephen for kissing his mother before he goes to bed, and one day he pushes Stephen into a filthy cesspool, causing Stephen to catch a bad fever.
Athy is a friendly boy whom Stephen meets in the infirmary at Clongowes. Athy likes Stephen Dedalus because they both have unusual names.
Brother Michael is the kindly brother who tends to Stephen and Athy in the Clongowes infirmary after Wells pushes Stephen into the cesspool.
Fleming is One of Stephen's friends at Clongowes.
Father Arnall is Stephen's stern Latin teacher at Clongowes. Later, when Stephen is at Belvedere College, Father Arnall delivers a series of lectures on death and hell that have a profound influence on Stephen.
Mike Flynn is a friend of Simon Dedalus's who tries, with little success, to train Stephen to be a runner during their summer at Blackrock.
Aubrey Mills is a young boy with whom Stephen plays imaginary adventure games at Blackrock.
Vincent Heron is a rival of Stephen's at Belvedere.
Boland and Nash is Two schoolmates of Stephen's at Belvedere, who taunt and bully him.
Cranly is Stephen's best friend at the university, in whom he confides his thoughts and feelings. In this sense, Cranly represents a secular confessor for Stephen. Eventually, Cranly begins to encourage Stephen to conform to the wishes of his family and to try harder to fit in with his peersâ€”advice that Stephen fiercely resents.
Davin is Another of Stephen's friends at the university. Davin comes from the Irish provinces and has a simple, solid nature. Stephen admires his talent for athletics, but disagrees with his unquestioning Irish patriotism, which Davin encourages Stephen to adopt.
Lynch is Another of Stephen's friends at the university, a coarse and often unpleasantly dry young man. Lynch is poorer than Stephen. Stephen explains his theory of aesthetics to Lynch in Chapter 5.
McCann is a fiercely political student at the university who tries to convince Stephen to be more concerned with politics.
Temple is a young man at the university who openly admires Stephen's keen independence and tries to copy his ideas and sentiments.
Dean of Studies is a Jesuit priest at University College.
Johnny Cashman is a friend of Simon Dedalus.